<p><a name="Pronunciation" id="Pronunciation"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Ghazal&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: Pronunciation">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Pronunciation</span></h2>
<p>The Arabic word <span lang="ar" xml:lang="ar">غزل</span> (<i>ġazal</i>) is pronounced <span title="Pronunciation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA"><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:IPA" title="Wikipedia:IPA">[ˈɣazal]</a></span>, roughly like the English word <i>guzzle</i>, but with the first, g-like consonant pronounced as a <a href="/wiki/Voiced_velar_fricative" title="Voiced velar fricative">voiced velar fricative</a>, i.e. without a complete closure between the tongue and the <a href="/wiki/Soft_palate" title="Soft palate">soft palate</a>. In South Asia, the name itself sounds exotic, as the voiced velar fricative is not found in native <a href="/wiki/Indic_languages" title="Indic languages" class="mw-redirect">Indic</a> words. In English, the word is often pronounced <span title="Pronunciation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA"><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:IPA_for_English" title="Wikipedia:IPA for English">/ˈɡæzæl/</a></span><sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> or <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">/ˈɡʌzʌl/</span><sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup>.</p>
<p><a name="Details_of_the_form" id="Details_of_the_form"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Ghazal&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: Details of the form">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Details of the form</span></h2>
